properties.howtogetthere:
Getting to Lihaga island is tricky: there are three possibilities
(1) take the **free** government ferry from Pelabuhan Munte ([[https://www.instagram.com/p/Cl21vrEr_0T/]]). Only in weekends and departs around 10am from Munte. Returns around 3-4pm from Lihaga to Munte. Check it and reserve your place before you come here! Get to Munte from Likupang by ojek or online taxi.
(2) share a ride with other people from Serei village (Dermaga Desa Serei). Probably only busy in the weekends and there isn't a guarantee that you might be able to join others. Only online taxis to Serei.
(3) go with a public boat from Likupang port to Gangga island and rent a small boat to Lihaga from there. You will have to sleep on Gangga island as there is no possibility to do this in a daytrip. There are public busses from Manado to Likupang.

There are 2 possibilities getting here:
(1) private trip from Calaca port (expensive)
(2) take a public boat to Bunaken village from Calaca port in Manado. As usual the public boats (Mo-Sa; will come here from Bunaken in the morning (8-9am) and go back there around 2-4pm. Only one boat a day so you will have to sleep in Bunaken village. Plenty of homestay/hostels and resorts here.

properties.howtogetthere:
There are 2 possibilities getting here:
(1) go on a daytrip from Manado (boats typically go from Dermaga Megamas Manado in the weekends), which normally includes 3 spots (Pasir Tumbul Nain, Siladen & Bunaken). This has limited flexibility as the main sightseeing is selfies on the beach there.
(2) take a public boat to Siladen village from Calaca port in Manado. As usual the public boats (Mo-Sa; will come here from Siladen in the morning (8-9am) and go back there around 2-4pm. Only one boat a day so you will have to sleep in Siladen village. There are some hostels/homestays on the island, apart from quiet some expensive resorts.

No official homestays/hostels here in Jiko. There were some homestays on the beaches but they are all closed/deserted (2025).
